body:
Yes, I see you are correct. My understanding was the `UncaughtExceptionHandler` would catch any `RuntimeException`s thrown by a `Thread` that is run in an `ExecutorService`. However, testing this locally using the below code indicates otherwise:

```
public static void main(String args[]) throws ExecutionException, InterruptedException {
  final Logger LOG = LoggerFactory.getLogger(ExecutorsUtils.class);

  ExecutorService service = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor(ExecutorsUtils.newThreadFactory(Optional.of(LOG)));
  service.submit(new Runnable() {
    @Override public void run() {
      LOG.info("Hello World!");
      throw new RuntimeException("Throwing Exception!");
    }
  });
  ExecutorsUtils.shutdownExecutorService(service, Optional.<Logger>absent());
}
```

Output:

```
0 [pool-2-thread-1] INFO gobblin.util.ExecutorsUtils  - Hello World!

Process finished with exit code 0
```

This seems to indicate that the `UncaughtExceptionHandler` is never even invoked in the above code. Interestingly, if `ExecutorService.execute(Runnable)` is used instead of `ExecutorService.submit(Runnable)` then the `UncaughtExceptionHandler` is invoked, and the exception is logged. These stack overflow posts confirms the above findings: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3929342/choose-between-executorservices-submit-and-executorservices-execute and http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1838923/why-is-uncaughtexceptionhandler-not-called-by-executorservice

My guess is that since `ExecutorService.submit(Runnable)` returns a `Future` the recommended way of handling `Exception`s is via `Future.get()`. Since `ExecutorService.execute(Runnable)` returns `void` it has to rely on the `UncaughtExceptionHandler`. I also confirmed that when invoked, the `UncaughtExceptionHandler` handles `RuntimeException`s and `Error`s properly.

This is problematic as we have followed the above pattern in many projects with the goal of handling any uncaught exceptions (ref internal JIRAs ETL-2559 and ETL-2560). For example, in Lumos we use the above pattern when running `CommitRunner`s in the `VirtualSnapshotJob`. Thats a big problem because we could have uncaught exceptions being thrown that we would never know about.

That being said, I will close this PR and create some internal JIRAs. Ideally, we would use `ExecutorService.submit(Runnable)` and use the returned `Future` object to handle any exceptions, but that is a more invasive change. The easiest fix is to just use `ExecutorService.execute(Runnable)` instead of `ExecutorService.submit(Runnable)`.
